                <head>No. 424.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Romero</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-03-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 27, 1883</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your note of the 22d instant relative to the reported further invasion of the
                    Mexican <pb facs="0756" n="686" xml:id="pg_686"/> State of Sonora by Apache
                    Indians from the San Carlos Agency in the Territory of Arizona.</p>
                <p>I have hastened to acquaint the Secretary of the Interior with the contents of
                    your note, and, in view of the frequency of the complaints of your Government of
                    the acts of those Indians, have suggested that the strictest measures be adopted
                    to prevent them from quitting their reservation and crossing into Mexico. I have
                    also furnished the Secretary of War with a copy of your note, and have asked
                    that whatever assistance may be properly given in the matter by his Dapartment
                    may be accorded to the ends of restraining future depredations by those
                    reservation Indians.</p>
                <p>Accept, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
